From: Opsero <noreply@opsero.com>
Date: Thu, 7 May 2026 12:00:00 -0400
Subject: [PATCH] xilinx_axienet: pulse optional QPLL reset GPIO once at first
 device reset

Some Opsero designs (sfp28-fmc-xxv on ZynqMP) feed the GTH gt_ref_clk from
a programmable Si5328 on the FMC card. The Linux i2c driver re-programs
the chip during probe, which briefly glitches the GT reference clock and
unlocks the GTH QPLL. The QPLL does not auto-recover.

When the AXI DMA's m_axi data clocks are sourced from the XXV's
tx_clk_out / rx_clk_out (recovered GT clocks), the DMA reset state machine
cannot complete because those clocks aren't running until the QPLL is
locked. The driver then reports "DMA reset timeout" and bails out of the
open path with a half-reset DMA, which can fault on later register access.

Fix by adding an optional "qpllreset-gpios" DT property and pulsing it at
the start of axienet_device_reset() — before __axienet_device_reset()
attempts the DMA reset. This re-locks the QPLL, gets the GT out of reset,
and starts tx_clk_out / rx_clk_out flowing so the DMA reset can complete.

Opt-in via DT — absence of the property leaves behavior unchanged.

The XXV IP exposes a single qpllreset_in_0 pin that resets the entire
shared GTH quad, so every port instance references the same GPIO line in
DT. gpiolib treats consumer requests as exclusive, so a per-instance
devm_gpiod_get_optional() would return -EBUSY for the 2nd–4th ports.
Instead the descriptor is held in a module-scope static, claimed by
whichever port probes first; the others just flag qpll_reset_pulse=true
and pulse through the shared handle, serialised by a module-scope mutex.

The pulse is one-shot per module load: the QPLL stays locked once it has
been re-locked after the Si5328 reconfiguration, and pulsing again would
briefly kill the GT clocks for any sibling port already carrying traffic
(or any port whose phylink is mid-resolve, which can SLVERR a register
read on the GT clock domain). The first device_reset() to run after probe
fires the pulse and sets axienet_qpll_reset_pulsed; subsequent resets,
including the in-band-status flap-induced ones on empty cages, leave the
GT alone.

Reference: AMD support forum
https://adaptivesupport.amd.com/s/question/0D54U000061gBW6SAM/xxv-mac-gt-reset-not-complete

Signed-off-by: Opsero <noreply@opsero.com>
---
 drivers/net/ethernet/xilinx/xilinx_axienet.h      |  3 ++
 drivers/net/ethernet/xilinx/xilinx_axienet_main.c | 71 +++++++++++++++++++++++
 2 files changed, 74 insertions(+)

diff --git a/drivers/net/ethernet/xilinx/xilinx_axienet.h b/drivers/net/ethernet/xilinx/xilinx_axienet.h
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/xilinx/xilinx_axienet.h
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/xilinx/xilinx_axienet.h
@@ -1157,6 +1157,9 @@ struct axienet_local {
 	u16 assigned_rx_port[XAE_MAX_QUEUES];
 	bool gt_reset_done;
 	bool use_gt_gpio;
+	/* True if this port's DT node carries qpllreset-gpios. The actual
+	 * GPIO descriptor is shared module-wide; see xilinx_axienet_main.c. */
+	bool qpll_reset_pulse;
 };

 /**
diff --git a/drivers/net/ethernet/xilinx/xilinx_axienet_main.c b/drivers/net/ethernet/xilinx/xilinx_axienet_main.c
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/xilinx/xilinx_axienet_main.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/xilinx/xilinx_axienet_main.c
@@ -104,6 +104,22 @@ EXPORT_SYMBOL(mrmac_pll_rst);

 static void axienet_rx_submit_desc(struct net_device *ndev);

+/* Shared QPLL reset GPIO state. The XXV IP exposes a single qpllreset_in_0
+ * pin that resets the entire shared GTH quad — every port instance refers
+ * to the same GPIO line in DT. The first port whose probe runs claims the
+ * descriptor; the others just flag qpll_reset_pulse=true and pulse via this
+ * shared handle. The mutex serialises pulses across ports.
+ *
+ * Pulsing is only needed once per module load — the QPLL stays locked
+ * after the first re-lock following the Si5328 refclk reconfiguration,
+ * and pulsing it again disrupts the GT clocks of any port that's already
+ * carrying traffic. axienet_qpll_reset_pulsed records that the one-shot
+ * pulse has fired so subsequent device_reset() calls leave the GT alone.
+ */
+static DEFINE_MUTEX(axienet_qpll_reset_lock);
+static struct gpio_desc *axienet_shared_qpll_reset_gpio;
+static bool axienet_qpll_reset_pulsed;
+
 /* Option table for setting up Axi Ethernet hardware options */
 static struct axienet_option axienet_options[] = {
 	/* Turn on jumbo packet support for both Rx and Tx */
@@ -1199,6 +1215,31 @@ static int axienet_device_reset(struct net_device *ndev)
 	struct axienet_dma_q *q;
 	u32 i;

+	/* If the board uses a programmable refclk source (e.g. Si5328) that
+	 * gets reconfigured during boot, the QPLL may have lost lock from
+	 * the resulting refclk glitch and won't auto-recover. Pulse the
+	 * shared QPLL reset GPIO BEFORE attempting any DMA/GT reset, so the
+	 * GT comes out of reset and tx_clk_out/rx_clk_out start running —
+	 * designs that wire those clocks to the AXI DMA m_axi data clocks
+	 * need them alive for the DMA reset state machine to complete.
+	 *
+	 * One-shot: only the first device_reset() to run after probe needs
+	 * to pulse — once the QPLL is locked it stays locked, and pulsing
+	 * again would briefly kill the GT clocks for any sibling port that
+	 * is already carrying traffic.
+	 */
+	if (lp->qpll_reset_pulse && axienet_shared_qpll_reset_gpio) {
+		mutex_lock(&axienet_qpll_reset_lock);
+		if (!axienet_qpll_reset_pulsed) {
+			gpiod_set_value_cansleep(axienet_shared_qpll_reset_gpio, 1);
+			udelay(10);
+			gpiod_set_value_cansleep(axienet_shared_qpll_reset_gpio, 0);
+			usleep_range(1000, 2000);
+			axienet_qpll_reset_pulsed = true;
+		}
+		mutex_unlock(&axienet_qpll_reset_lock);
+	}
+
 	if (lp->axienet_config->mactype == XAXIENET_MRMAC) {
 		/* Reset MRMAC */
 		axienet_mrmac_reset(lp);
@@ -5873,6 +5914,35 @@ static int axienet_probe(struct platform_device *pdev)
 		goto cleanup_mdio;
 	}

+	/* Optional QPLL reset GPIO. Pulsed once at the first device_reset()
+	 * to re-lock the GTH QPLL after the GT reference clock has been
+	 * glitched (e.g. by mid-boot reconfiguration of a programmable clock
+	 * source). The IP's qpllreset_in_0 pin resets the entire shared GTH
+	 * quad, so every port's DT node references the same GPIO line — the
+	 * first port to probe claims the descriptor for the whole module,
+	 * the others just flag themselves to pulse via the shared handle.
+	 */
+	if (of_property_present(pdev->dev.of_node, "qpllreset-gpios")) {
+		lp->qpll_reset_pulse = true;
+
+		mutex_lock(&axienet_qpll_reset_lock);
+		if (!axienet_shared_qpll_reset_gpio) {
+			struct gpio_desc *g;
+
+			g = devm_gpiod_get(&pdev->dev, "qpllreset",
+					   GPIOD_OUT_LOW);
+			if (IS_ERR(g)) {
+				ret = PTR_ERR(g);
+				mutex_unlock(&axienet_qpll_reset_lock);
+				dev_err(&pdev->dev, "Failed to get qpllreset GPIO (%d)\n",
+					ret);
+				goto cleanup_phylink;
+			}
+			axienet_shared_qpll_reset_gpio = g;
+		}
+		mutex_unlock(&axienet_qpll_reset_lock);
+	}
+
 	ret = register_netdev(lp->ndev);
 	if (ret) {
 		dev_err(lp->dev, "register_netdev() error (%i)\n", ret);
--
2.43.0
